{{short description|19th-century painting by Winslow Homer}} {{Infobox artwork | title = Northeaster | image_file = Northeaster by Winslow Homer 1895.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = 388px | alt = | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | artist = [[Winslow Homer]] | year = {{Start date|1895}} | height_metric = 87.6 | width_metric = 128 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | condition = | city = [[ New York City]], US | museum = [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | accession = 10.64.5 | coordinates = | owner = | url = {{URL|www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/11130}}}}
'''''Northeaster''''' is one of several paintings on marine subjects by the late-19th-century American painter [[Winslow Homer]]. Like ''[[The Fog Warning]]'' and ''[[Breezing Up]]'', he created it during his time in [[Maine]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Winslow_Homer.aspx |title=Winslow Homer |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of World Biography |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|The Gale Group Inc.]] |year=2004}}</ref> It is on display in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York. Viewers are presented a struggle of elements between the sea and the rocky shore.<ref name="eb">{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Winslow-Homer |title=Winslow Homer |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |date=May 30, 2018 |first1=Jules David |last1=Prown |author2=The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica}}</ref> Winslow Homer excelled in painting landscape paintings that depicted seascapes and mountain scenery. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/06/travel/06culture.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Winslow Homer’s Maine |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Geraldine |last=Fabrikant |date=September 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://spartacus-educational.com/USACWhomer.htm |title=Winslow Homer |publisher=Spartacus Educational |first=John |last=Simkin |date=August 2014}}</ref>
==Background and description== After extensive travel, Homer settled in [[Prouts Neck]], Maine. He had a studio built for him, which was completed in 1884, and painted marine subjects, including the hard lives of the fishermen and their families. He increasingly chose to depict the sea itself, and was especially attracted to stormy seas. During this period he painted a wide array of seascapes such as ''The Gulf Stream'' (1899), ''Moonlight&nbsp;– Wood's Island Light'' (1886), ''Northeaster'' (1895) and ''Early Morning After a Storm at Sea'' (1902). Many of his paintings depict the battlefront of the sea and the shore, and the waves crashing onto the rocky shore. It has been said that they "are among the strongest expressions in all art of the power and dangerous beauty of the sea".<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www1.umassd.edu/specialprograms/mawh/librarydocs/2goodrichessay.pdf |author=Goodrich, Lloyd |title=Winslow Homer |publisher=George Braziller, Inc. |year=1959}}</ref> ''Northeaster'' shows the waves while the [[Northeaster]] blows. Northeasters are storms along the upper East Coast of the United States that derive their name from the direction of the wind as it rotates onto land. The painting dates from 1895, but Homer reworked it by 1901.<ref name=Met>{{cite web |url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/11130 |title=Northeaster |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]}}</ref><ref name="eb"/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Hoover Giese |first=Lucretia |date=2005 |title=Meeting the New Century: Winslow Homer's Drawing after Northeaster |journal=Visual Resources |volume=21 |pages=347-362 |doi=10.1080/01973760500298146 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233201256_Meeting_the_New_Century_Winslow_Homer's_Drawing_after_Northeaster |via=[[ResearchGate]]}}</ref>
==Provenance== ''Northeaster'' was at [[Knoedler|M. Knoedler and Company]] of New York in 1895 and then in 1895–96 with [[Thomas B. Clarke]], also in New York. It was then returned to Homer in Maine. In 1900 it was again with Knoedler. From 1901 to 1910 it was owned by George A. Hearn, also of New York, who gave it to the Metropolitan Museum.<ref name=Met/>
