The '''Symphony No. 6''' is an [[orchestra]]l [[symphony]] in six movements by the American composer [[Howard Hanson]]. The work was commissioned by the [[New York Philharmonic]] under the direction of [[Leonard Bernstein]] for the orchestra's 125th anniversary.<ref name="Chicago Tribune">{{cite web |last=Rhein |first=John von |title=Howard Hanson: Symphony No. 3, Symphony No. 6, "Fantasy Variations on a Theme of Youth" |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=February 3, 1991 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-02-03/entertainment/9101100657_1_delos-new-york-chamber-symphony-gerard-schwarz |accessdate=February 21, 2016}}</ref> It was composed in 1967 and was given its world premiere on February 29, 1968, by the New York Philharmonic conducted by Hanson.
==Structure== The symphony has a duration of roughly 20 minutes and is composed in six continuous [[Movement (music)|movements]]: #Andante #Allegro scherzando #Adagio #Allegro assai #Adagio #Allegro
==Reception== The Symphony No. 6 has been praised by music critics. John von Rhein of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called it "one of [Hanson's] most formally innovative" symphonies.<ref name="Chicago Tribune" /> Andrew Achenbach of ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'' similarly wrote, "it boasts a formidable thematic economy and intriguing formal scheme of which Hanson himself was justifiably proud."<ref>{{cite web |last=Achenbach |first=Andrew |title=Music of Howard Hanson - Volume 1 |work=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]] |date=September 1998 |url=http://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/music-of-howard-hanson-volume-1 |accessdate=February 21, 2016}}</ref>
